            "text": "1Chronicles 29:2",
            "children": []
          },
          {
            "element": "span",
            "class": "",
            "text": "; and ",
            "children": []
          },
          {
            "element": "span",
            "class": "verse-link",
            "text": "1Kings 10:11",
            "children": []
          },
          {
            "element": "span",
            "class": "",
            "text": ", which relates that Hiram’s fleet brought “precious stones” from Ophir for Solomon. But no mention of this kind of decoration is made in 1 Kings 6. The Vulgate explains the phrase as meaning a floor of costly marble.",
            "children": []
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "element": "p",
        "class": "",
        "text": "Gold of Parvaim.—Perhaps Farwâ, an auriferous region in S. Arabia. Others connect the word with the Sanskrit pûrva, “eastern,” and seek Parvaim, like Ophir, in India. The name does not recur in the Old Testament.",
        "children": [
          {
            "element": "span",
            "class": "bld",
            "text": "Gold of Parvaim.",
            "children": []
          },
          {
            "element": "span",
            "class": "ital",
            "text": "—",
            "children": []
          },
          {
            "element": "span",
            "class": "",
            "text": "Perhaps ",
            "children": []
          },
          {
            "element": "span",
            "class": "ital",
            "text": "Farwâ,",
            "children": []
          },
          {
            "element": "span",
            "class": "",
            "text": " an auriferous region in S. Arabia. Others connect the word with the Sanskrit ",
            "children": []
          },
          {
            "element": "span",
            "class": "ital",
            "text": "pûrva,",
            "children": []
          },
          {
            "element": "span",
            "class": "",
            "text": " “eastern,” and seek Parvaim, like Ophir, in India. The name does not recur in the Old Testament.",
            "children": []
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "element": "p",
        "class": "",
        "text": "",
        "children": []
      }
    ]
