  {
    "type": "EXEGETICAL (ORIGINAL LANGUAGES)",
    "name": "Pulpit Commentary",
    "elements": [
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "cmt_sub_title",
        "text": "Verse 6.",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": " - ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "cmt_word",
        "text": "He garnished",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ". The verb employed is (e) of ver. 4, ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "accented",
        "text": "supra",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": " (",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "Revelation 21:19",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "). ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "cmt_word",
        "text": "Precious stones",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ". The exact manner in which these were applied or fixed is not stated. What the precious stones were, however, need not be doubtful (",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "1 Chronicles 29:2",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "; the obvious references for which passage, ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "Isaiah 54:11, 12",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": " and ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "Revelation 21:18-21",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ", cannot be forgotten. See also ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "Ezekiel 27:16",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "; ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "Song of Solomon 5:14",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "; ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "Lamentations 4:7",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "). ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "cmt_word",
        "text": "For beauty",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "; ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "accented",
        "text": "i.e.",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": " to add beauty to the house. ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "cmt_word",
        "text": "Parvaim",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ". What this word designates, or, if a place, where the place was, is not known. Gesenius ('Lexicon,' ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "accented",
        "text": "sub vet.",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ") would derive it from a Sanskrit word, purva, meaning \"oriental.\" Hitzig suggests another Sanskrit word, ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "accented",
        "text": "paru",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ", meaning \"hill,\" and indicating the \"twin hills\" of Arabia (Prof., 6:7. § 11) as the derivation. And Knobel suggests that it is a form of ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "accented",
        "text": "Sepharvaim",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ", the Syriac and Jonathan Targum version of ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "accented",
        "text": "Sephar",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": " (",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "Genesis 10:30",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "). The word does not occur in any other Bible passage (see Dr. Smith's 'Bible Dictionary,' vol. it. p. 711). 2 Chronicles 3:6",
        "children": []
